  4→  Handle image resizing if the image exceeds the window dimensions.
  5→
  6→  If we are using the Chrome engine, add the "chrome" class to the
  7→  body and defer image resizing to pure CSS. The Chrome engine can
  8→  handle image resizing on its own, but for older versions of WebView,
  9→  we do it here.
 10→
 11→  If we are resizing with JavaScript, we also account for the CSS zoom
 12→  level applied to the image. If an image is scaled with CSS zoom, the
 13→  dimensions given to us by the browser will not be scaled
 14→  accordingly, giving us only the original dimensions. We have to
 15→  fetch the zoom value and scale the dimensions with it before
 16→  checking if the image exceeds the window bounds.
 17→
 18→  If the WebView loads too early on Android <= 2.3 (which happens on
 19→  the first card or regularly with WebView switching enabled), then
 20→  the window dimensions returned to us are 0x0. In this case, we skip
 21→  image resizing and try again after we know the window has fully
 22→  loaded with a method call initiated from Java (onPageFinished).
 23→*/
 24→var resizeImages = function () {
 25→    if (navigator.userAgent.indexOf("Chrome") > -1) {
 26→        document.body.className = document.body.className + " chrome";
 27→    } else {
 28→        if (window.innerWidth === 0 || window.innerHeight === 0) {
 29→            return;
 30→        }
 31→        var maxWidth = window.innerWidth * 0.9;
 32→        var maxHeight = window.innerHeight * 0.9;
 33→        var ratio = 0;
 34→        var images = document.getElementsByTagName("img");
 35→        for (var i = 0; i < images.length; i++) {
 36→            var img = images[i];
