{"file_path": "/project/user_actions_example.html", "content": "<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>AnkiDroid User Actions Example</title>
    <style>
        .user-action-demo {
            margin: 20px 0;
            padding: 15px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        .cloze-hidden {
            color: blue;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        .cloze-revealed {
            background-color: yellow;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="card">
        <h2>User Actions Demo Card</h2>

        <div class="user-action-demo">
            <p>This card demonstrates the User Action functionality similar to AnkiMobile.</p>

            <p>The following text has cloze deletions that can be revealed one by one:</p>
            <p>The capital of France is <span class="cloze-hidden" id="cloze1">[...]</span>, 
               which is known for the <span class="cloze-hidden" id="cloze2">[...]</span> tower.</p>

            <p><strong>Instructions:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Use a gesture or keyboard shortcut bound to "User Action 1" to reveal the next cloze</li>
                <li>Use "User Action 2" to show a hint</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div id="hint-box" style="display: none; background-color: #f0f0f0; padding: 10px; margin: 10px 0;">
            <strong>Hint:</strong> Think about famous landmarks and European capitals.
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Define user actions that can be triggered by AnkiDroid
        var currentClozeIndex = 0;
        var clozeAnswers = ["Paris", "Eiffel"];

        // User Action 1: Reveal next cloze deletion
        var userJs1 = function() {
            if (currentClozeIndex < clozeAnswers.length) {
                var clozeId = "cloze" + (currentClozeIndex + 1);
                var clozeElement = document.getElementById(clozeId);
                if (clozeElement) {
                    clozeElement.textContent = clozeAnswers[currentClozeIndex];
                    clozeElement.className = "cloze-revealed";
                    currentClozeIndex++;
                }
            }
        };

        // User Action 2: Show hint
        var userJs2 = function() {
            document.getElementById("hint-box").style.display = "block";
        };

        // User Action 3: Reset all clozes (for demonstration)
        var userJs3 = function() {
            for (var i = 1; i <= clozeAnswers.length; i++) {
                var clozeElement = document.getElementById("cloze" + i);
                if (clozeElement) {
                    clozeElement.textContent = "[...]";
                    clozeElement.className = "cloze-hidden";
                }
            }
            currentClozeIndex = 0;
            document.getElementById("hint-box").style.display = "none";
        };

        // Click handlers for manual testing (optional)
        document.getElementById("cloze1").onclick = function() {
            userJs1();
        };
        document.getElementById("cloze2").onclick = function() {
            userJs1();
        };
    </script>
</body>
</html>"}

{"file_path": "/project/USER_ACTIONS_README.md", "content": "# AnkiDroid User Actions Implementation

This implementation adds User Action functionality to AnkiDroid, similar to the feature available in AnkiMobile 2.0.88+.

## Overview

User Actions allow you to trigger custom JavaScript functions defined in your card templates using keyboard shortcuts, gestures, or external controllers. This is especially useful for:

- Progressive disclosure of cloze deletions
- Showing hints or additional information
- Interactive card features
- Custom study workflows

## How to Use

### 1. Define JavaScript Functions in Your Card Template

In your card template (front or back), define functions named `userJs1` through `userJs9`:

```html
<script>
// User Action 1: Reveal next cloze
var userJs1 = function() {
    // Your custom code here
    revealNextCloze();
};

// User Action 2: Show hint
var userJs2 = function() {
    // Your custom code here
    showHint();
};

// More user actions as needed...
var userJs3 = function() {
    // Custom action 3
};
</script>
```

### 2. Configure Bindings in AnkiDroid

1. Go to **Settings → Controls**
2. Scroll down to the **User Actions** section
3. Tap on **User Action 1**, **User Action 2**, etc.
4. Assign a gesture or keyboard shortcut to trigger the action

### 3. Use During Study

When studying cards that have the appropriate `userJs` functions defined:
- Use your configured gesture or key binding
- The corresponding JavaScript function will be executed
- Only functions that are defined and are actual functions will be called

## Example Use Cases

### Progressive Cloze Revelation
```javascript
var currentCloze = 0;
var clozeAnswers = ["Paris", "France", "Europe"];

var userJs1 = function() {
    if (currentCloze < clozeAnswers.length) {
        document.getElementById("cloze" + currentCloze).textContent = clozeAnswers[currentCloze];
        currentCloze++;
    }
};
```

### Show/Hide Hints
```javascript
var userJs2 = function() {
    var hint = document.getElementById("hint");
    if (hint.style.display === "none") {
        hint.style.display = "block";
    } else {
        hint.style.display = "none";
    }
};
```

### Audio Control
```javascript
var userJs3 = function() {
    var audio = document.getElementById("pronunciation");
    if (audio) {
        audio.play();
    }
};
```

## Safety Features

- Functions are only executed if they exist and are actually functions
- Uses `typeof userJsX === 'function'` check before execution
- No error if the function is not defined
- Safe fallback behavior

## Available User Actions

- **User Action 1** through **User Action 9**
- Each can be bound to different gestures/keys
- Each corresponds to `userJs1` through `userJs9` JavaScript functions

## Compatibility

This implementation follows the same pattern as AnkiMobile:
- Same function naming convention (`userJs1`, `userJs2`, etc.)
- Same safety checks
- Same flexibility for custom implementations

## Technical Details

### Signal Flow
1. User triggers gesture/key binding
2. AnkiDroid executes corresponding ViewerCommand (USER_ACTION_1, etc.)
3. JavaScript execution: `if (typeof userJsX === 'function') userJsX();`
4. Custom function runs in the WebView context

### JavaScript API
The user actions have access to the full DOM and any JavaScript APIs available in the WebView, including:
- DOM manipulation
- CSS changes
- Audio/video control
- Local storage
- Any custom JavaScript libraries included in the template

## Migration from AnkiMobile

If you have cards that already work with AnkiMobile user actions, they should work with AnkiDroid without any modifications to the card templates. Only the binding configuration needs to be set up in AnkiDroid's settings."}
